<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06107080 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06107080 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; GAME; RESULT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Chicago White Sox remained the only perfect team in the majors, sloshingpast New York 6-5 Monday and spoiling the Yankees' home opener.;    A steadyrain failed to dampen Chicago's best start since 1982, when it won eight in arow. Bobby Thigpen ended the game by striking out Steve Sax with the basesloaded as the White Sox improved to 5-0.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  WHITE SOX STAY PERFECT WITH 6-5 WIN  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  A.L. Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     Scott Fletcher, who went 4 for 4, and Robin Ventura both hit two-run homersoff Yankees starter Scott Sanderson.;  INDIANS 1, RED SOX 0: Brook Jacobybroke up the longest scoreless tie in Fenway Park since 1983, hitting a homerun in the 13th inning as Cleveland won in Boston.;    Steve Olin (1-0) bailedout starter Charles Nagy with one out in the ninth inning and held the Red Soxhitless for 3 2/3 innings before giving way to Doug Jones in the 13th.;   Boston starter Matt Young allowed two hits and six walks in nine innings.;   The 12 scoreless innings were the most in Boston since Texas beat the Red Sox1-0 in 14 innings on April 17, 1983.;  ORIOLES 7, BREWERS 2: Sam Horn hit agrand slam and Glenn Davis got his first American League homer as Baltimorebeat Milwaukee in the Brewers' home opener.;    Cal Ripken added a two-runhomer and two singles as the Orioles handed Chris Bosio his first loss inApril since 1988.;  BLUE JAYS 4, TIGERS 3: Kelly Gruber homered for the secondconsecutive game as Toronto beat host Detroit and improved to 6-2, the beststart in club history.;  MARINERS 8, TWINS 4: Edgar Martinez and Tracy Joneshit home runs as host Seattle beat Minnesota for its first win.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDA